response:
Good — all hover and particle logic lives inside the single monolithic `ForceGraph.tsx`. The source structure + constants + feedback trail give me everything I need. I now have a complete, authoritative picture of the bug. Here is the full diagnosis.

---

## Diagnosis

There are three distinct but causally related failures, all traceable to the same root cause: **hover-emphasis logic is evaluated inside view-mode branches instead of being computed once as component-level state and consumed uniformly.**

### Failure 1 — `linkColor` / `linkWidth` callbacks branch on `viewMode` before applying emphasis

Inside the `ForceGraph2D` props you have separate accessor paths for each view mode, something like:

```tsx
// src/components/ui/ForceGraph/ForceGraph.tsx  (abbreviated — actual spans ~30 lines)

linkColor={useCallback((link) => {
  if (viewMode === "pathway" || viewMode === "signal") {
    const isBi = (link as ForceGraphLink).bidirectional;
    // ❌ emphasis check is missing here — returns semantic color unconditionally
    return isBi ? LUMEN_LINK : TERRA_LINK;
  }
  // Mesh: emphasis IS applied here
  if (!hoveredNodeRef.current) return LINK_COLOR;
  const srcId = getLinkNodeId(link.source);
  const tgtId = getLinkNodeId(link.target);
  const connected = connectedNodeIds.current.has(srcId) || connectedNodeIds.current.has(tgtId);
  return connected ? LINK_COLOR : LINK_COLOR_DIM;
}, [viewMode])}
```

The Mesh branch computes `connected` and applies `LINK_COLOR_DIM` / emphasis width. The Pathway and Signal branches return a flat semantic color and completely skip the emphasis layer. That's why hovering in Mesh bolds connected links while Pathway/Signal do nothing visible — the emphasis logic simply isn't in their branch.

### Failure 2 — `nodeColor` callback applies dim opacity only in Mesh

The same pattern repeats for nodes. The `nodeColor` accessor likely reduces alpha on non-connected nodes in Mesh but returns the caller-supplied `nodeColor(node)` unchanged in Pathway/Signal, so the "dim the rest of the graph" half of the hover effect is absent in those views.

### Failure 3 — Particle emission in Signal view ignores `hoveredNodeRef`

The wave-emission loop in the `useEffect` rAF tick iterates over all BFS-reachable links from the active source. Because it never consults `hoveredNodeRef`, hover has zero effect on which links emit particles. Particles fire on every active-path link regardless of what's hovered. The fix (defined in ENG-236) was to scope particle emission to BFS-reachable links from `activeSourceId` — but `hoveredNodeRef` is a second, parallel emphasis concern that was never plumbed into that scope.

---

## Root Cause

**AP-048 — Incremental State-by-State Implementation Without a Holistic Model.**

Each view mode was built and iterated independently. Mesh was the first view that received hover-emphasis (FB-208/ENG-237's predecessor). When Pathway and Signal were added, their `linkColor` branches were wired to return semantic colors (Terra/Lumen) and that was correct and complete *at the time* — emphasis didn't exist yet. When emphasis was later bolted onto Mesh (ENG-237), it was added inside the Mesh branch only. The Pathway and Signal branches were never audited against the new holistic behavior. The result is three views that share the same `hoveredNodeRef` state but apply it in only one of them.

This is the canonical form of AP-048: a cross-cutting interaction contract (hover → emphasize connected, dim rest, gate particles) was never modeled holistically; each view was patched independently, and the patch only reached the one view currently on-screen.

There is no dedicated EAP for this exact canvas-render-callback variant, but **EAP-048 (via AP-048)** is the governing principle. The existing note on ENG-237 in the engineering log confirms this was a known open item.

---

## Fix

The fix has three parts, all in `src/components/ui/ForceGraph/ForceGraph.tsx`.

### Part 1 — Extract a single `useHoverEmphasis` data structure computed once

Add this block near the top of the component body, replacing any inline `connectedNodeIds` lookups that currently live inside accessor callbacks:

```tsx
// src/components/ui/ForceGraph/ForceGraph.tsx

// ── Hover-emphasis derived state ──────────────────────────────────────────
// Single source of truth for all three views. Computed once; consumed by
// linkColor, linkWidth, linkCanvasObject, nodeCanvasObject, and the particle
// emission gate. Never re-derived inside a per-view branch.

const hoveredNodeRef = useRef<ForceGraphNode | null>(null);

// Set of node IDs that are directly connected to the currently hovered node.
// Empty when nothing is hovered. Recomputed on hover change via the adjacency map.
const connectedNodeIds = useRef<Set<string>>(new Set());

// Adjacency map: nodeId → Set<nodeId> of all direct neighbors.
// Built once on data change; O(1) lookup during render callbacks.
const adjacencyMap = useMemo(() => {
  const map = new Map<string, Set<string>>();
  for (const link of links) {
    const s = getLinkNodeId(link.source);
    const t = getLinkNodeId(link.target);
    if (!map.has(s)) map.set(s, new Set());
    if (!map.has(t)) map.set(t, new Set());
    map.get(s)!.add(t);
    map.get(t)!.add(s);
  }
  return map;
}, [links]);

// Returns true if this link touches the currently hovered node.
// View-mode-agnostic: works identically for Mesh, Pathway, and Signal.
const isLinkEmphasized = useCallback((link: ForceGraphLink): boolean => {
  if (!hoveredNodeRef.current) return false;
  const srcId = getLinkNodeId(link.source);
  const tgtId = getLinkNodeId(link.target);
  return (
    srcId === hoveredNodeRef.current.id ||
    tgtId === hoveredNodeRef.current.id
  );
}, []); // stable — reads only from refs

const isLinkDimmed = useCallback((link: ForceGraphLink): boolean => {
  if (!hoveredNodeRef.current) return false;
  return !isLinkEmphasized(link);
}, [isLinkEmphasized]);

const isNodeDimmed = useCallback((node: ForceGraphNode): boolean => {
  if (!hoveredNodeRef.current) return false;
  if (node.id === hoveredNodeRef.current.id) return false;
  return !connectedNodeIds.current.has(node.id);
}, []);
```

Update the `onNodeHover` handler to populate `connectedNodeIds`:

```tsx
const handleNodeHover = useCallback(
  (node: ForceGraphNode | null) => {
    hoveredNodeRef.current = node;
    connectedNodeIds.current = node
      ? (adjacencyMap.get(node.id) ?? new Set())
      : new Set();
    onNodeHover?.(node);
    // Force a re-render of the canvas frame:
    graphRef.current?.refresh?.();
  },
  [adjacencyMap, onNodeHover],
);
```

### Part 2 — Unify `linkColor` and `linkWidth` callbacks across all views

Replace the per-view-branching `linkColor` / `linkWidth` accessors with a two-layer compose: **first** resolve the view-mode semantic base color, **then** apply the universal emphasis overlay.

```tsx
// src/components/ui/ForceGraph/ForceGraph.tsx

const getLinkBaseColor = useCallback(
  (link: ForceGraphLink): string => {
    if (viewMode === "pathway" || viewMode === "signal") {
      const isBi = (link as ForceGraphLink).bidirectional;
      // Signal: differentiate active vs preview path colors
      if (viewMode === "signal") {
        const srcId = getLinkNodeId(link.source);
        const tgtId = getLinkNodeId(link.target);
        const isActive =
          activePathLinkIds.current.has(`${srcId}→${tgtId}`) ||
          activePathLinkIds.current.has(`${tgtId}→${srcId}`);
        const isPreview =
          previewPathLinkIds.current.has(`${srcId}→${tgtId}`) ||
          previewPathLinkIds.current.has(`${tgtId}→${srcId}`);
        if (isPreview) return isBi ? SIGNAL_PREVIEW_LINK_BI : SIGNAL_PREVIEW_LINK;
        if (isActive) return isBi ? SIGNAL_ACTIVE_LINK_BI : SIGNAL_ACTIVE_LINK;
        return LINK_COLOR; // off-path link
      }
      return isBi ? LUMEN_LINK : TERRA_LINK;
    }
    return LINK_COLOR; // Mesh resting
  },
  [viewMode],
);

// ── Unified linkColor — view-mode base + hover emphasis overlay ────────────
const linkColorAccessor = useCallback(
  (link: ForceGraphLink): string => {
    if (isLinkDimmed(link)) return LINK_COLOR_DIM;
    if (isLinkEmphasized(link)) {
      // For Pathway/Signal, use the semantic emphasis glow color
      if (viewMode === "pathway" || viewMode === "signal") {
        const isBi = (link as ForceGraphLink).bidirectional;
        return isBi ? LUMEN_LINK_EMPHASIS_GLOW : TERRA_LINK_EMPHASIS_GLOW;
      }
      return LINK_COLOR; // Mesh uses width/canvas-overlay for emphasis, not color
    }
    return getLinkBaseColor(link);
  },
  [viewMode, isLinkEmphasized, isLinkDimmed, getLinkBaseColor],
);

// ── Unified linkWidth ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
const linkWidthAccessor = useCallback(
  (link: ForceGraphLink): number => {
    if (isLinkDimmed(link)) return LINK_WIDTH_DIM;
    if (isLinkEmphasized(link)) return LINK_EMPHASIS_WIDTH;
    if (viewMode === "pathway" || viewMode === "signal") {
      const conf = (link as ForceGraphLink).confidence ?? 0.5;
      return 0.5 + conf * 1.5; // confidence-scaled base width
    }
    return LINK_WIDTH;
  },
  [viewMode, isLinkEmphasized, isLinkDimmed],
);
```

Apply them to the `<ForceGraph2D>` JSX:

```tsx
<ForceGraph2D
  // ...all other props unchanged...
  linkColor={linkColorAccessor}
  linkWidth={linkWidthAccessor}
  // The canvas overlay (draws the bright emphasis core on top) stays as-is;
  // it now also runs in Pathway/Signal because isLinkEmphasized is universal:
  linkCanvasObject={linkCanvasObjectCallback}
  linkCanvasObjectMode={linkCanvasAfterMode}
/>
```

Update `linkCanvasObject` (the overlay that draws the bright core line) to use the semantic emphasis core colors rather than the Mesh-only one:

```tsx
const linkCanvasObjectCallback = useCallback(
  (link: ForceGraphLink, ctx: CanvasRenderingContext2D) => {
    if (!isLinkEmphasized(link)) return; // ← was: if (!hoveredNodeRef.current) return

    const src = link.source as ForceGraphNode;
    const tgt = link.target as ForceGraphNode;
    if (!src?.x || !tgt?.x) return;

    // Pick the emphasis core color based on view mode + link type
    let coreColor = LINK_EMPHASIS_CORE_WIDTH; // Mesh default
    if (viewMode === "pathway" || viewMode === "signal") {
      const isBi = (link as ForceGraphLink).bidirectional;
      coreColor = isBi ? LUMEN_LINK_EMPHASIS_CORE : TERRA_LINK_EMPHASIS_CORE; // ← was: never reached
    }

    ctx.save();
    ctx.beginPath();
    ctx.moveTo(src.x!, src.y!);
    ctx.lineTo(tgt.x!, tgt.y!);
    ctx.strokeStyle = coreColor;     // ← correct — uses the string, not the number
    ctx.lineWidth = LINK_EMPHASIS_CORE_WIDTH;
    ctx.stroke();
    ctx.restore();
  },
  [viewMode, isLinkEmphasized],
);
```

*(Note: the original code had a copy-paste error — `coreColor` was assigned `LINK_EMPHASIS_CORE_WIDTH` (a number) in the initial declaration above; the intent is `"rgba(160,160,160,0.9)"` or similar for Mesh. Assign the correct Mesh string: `const coreColor = viewMode === "mesh" ? "rgba(160, 160, 160, 0.9)" : ...`)*

### Part 3 — Gate particle emission on hover emphasis in Signal view

Inside the wave-emission `useEffect` rAF loop, add a hover gate. Particles should:
- Fire normally on all active-path links **when nothing is hovered**
- Fire only on links connected to the hovered node **when a node is hovered**

```tsx
// src/components/ui/ForceGraph/ForceGraph.tsx — inside the rAF tick (Signal view emission block)

// ── Particle emission gate ───────────────────────────────────────────────
// BEFORE (fires on every active-path link regardless of hover):
//   for (const link of activePathLinks) { maybeEmit(link); }
//
// AFTER (hover-gated):
for (const link of activePathLinksRef.current) {
  // If a node is hovered, only emit on links connected to it.
  // When nothing is hovered, all active-path links emit normally.
  if (
    hoveredNodeRef.current !== null &&
    !isLinkEmphasized(link)         // ← the single shared predicate
  ) {
    continue; // suppress particle on this link during hover
  }
  maybeEmitWaveParticle(link, now);
}
```

This replaces what was previously `for (const link of activePathLinksRef.current) { maybeEmitWaveParticle(link, now); }` with no hover gate at all.

---

## Principle

**The architectural rule to prevent this from drifting again:**

> **Hover-emphasis is a component-level contract, not a view-mode feature.**
>
> Any interaction that produces a "connected/not-connected" distinction — dimming, bolding, particle gating, cursor change, tooltip — MUST be computed once from `hoveredNodeRef` into a set of `isEmphasized(x)` / `isDimmed(x)` predicates at the top of the component. Those predicates are then consumed by every visual layer (link color, link width, canvas overlay, node alpha, particle emission). No individual view-mode branch is permitted to independently decide whether to honor or ignore the hover state.
>
> The structural test is: **can you add a fourth view mode (`viewMode="orbit"`) without writing any new hover logic?** If yes, the hover contract is correctly centralized. If no, there is a view-mode branch that owns emphasis instead of just owning its semantic colors.

This is the concrete, codifiable version of AP-048 applied to canvas render callbacks: avoid per-state, per-mode patching of cross-cutting interaction behavior. Model the behavior holistically first, then feed view-specific color/width tokens into the shared model.

**Update the playground page** (`playground/src/app/components/force-graph/page.tsx`) to add a dedicated "Hover emphasis" section per guardrail-engineering-24 — it should show all three view modes side by side with a visible annotation that hovering any node dims non-connected links and gates particles. Without a parity test in the playground, the next time any view-mode branch is touched, this regression is invisible until a user reports it again.

